Yes, the break statement can be used in nested loops. When break is encountered in a nested loop, it will only exit the innermost loop it is contained in.

For example:

for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
        if (j == 1) {
            break; // exits the inner loop (j-loop) only
        }
        printf("%d ", j);
    }
    printf("\n");
}

In this example, when j is equal to 1, the inner loop will exit, but the outer loop (i-loop) will continue running.

If you want to exit both loops, you can use a variable as a flag to indicate whether the outer loop should continue or not:

int exit_outer = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 3 && !exit_outer; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
        if (j == 1) {
            exit_outer = 1; // set flag to exit outer loop
            break; // exits the inner loop
        }
        printf("%d ", j);
    }
    printf("\n");
}
